  "prompt": "How often should one visit a dentist?",
  "response": "Regular dental visits are crucial for maintaining good oral health. The general recommendation is to visit the dentist **every six months** for a routine check-up and professional cleaning. However, the frequency may vary based on individual needs and oral health conditions. Here are some guidelines:\n\n1. **Every 6 months**: This is the standard recommendation for most people with good oral health. It allows for early detection of issues like cavities, gum disease, or oral cancer.\n\n2. **Every 3\u20134 months**: If you have a history of gum disease, are undergoing orthodontic treatment, or are at higher risk for dental problems (e.g., smokers, diabetics, or those with a weak immune system), more frequent visits may be necessary.\n\n3. **As recommended by your dentist**: If you have specific dental conditions or concerns (e.g., frequent cavities, dry mouth, or dental anxiety), your dentist may suggest a personalized schedule.\n\nAdditionally, you should see a dentist promptly if you experience any of the following:\n- Tooth pain or sensitivity.\n- Swollen, bleeding, or receding gums.\n- Loose or cracked teeth.\n- Mouth sores or unusual changes in your oral tissues.\n\nRegular visits help prevent dental issues and ensure your teeth and gums stay healthy.",
